# Change Request (CHG) — Install MSBuild 17 (VS 2022 Build Tools)

---

## 1. Change Summary

**Short Description:**
Install Visual Studio 2022 Build Tools (MSBuild v17) on production GitHub Actions self-hosted runner (Windows Server 2019)

**Description:**
Install the Visual Studio 2022 Build Tools package on the production Windows Server 2019 self-hosted GitHub Actions runner to make MSBuild v17.x available for .NET build pipelines.

This is a net-new software installation alongside the existing Build Tools. The current (older) MSBuild version will remain installed and unchanged. No existing pipelines will be modified as part of this change. Teams that wish to use MSBuild 17 will explicitly opt in by updating their workflow YAML to target vs-version `[17.0,)`. All other pipelines will be updated to pin vs-version `[16.0,17.0)` to ensure they continue resolving to the current MSBuild version.

IMPORTANT: The `microsoft/setup-msbuild@v2` GitHub Action uses `vswhere -latest` when no vs-version is specified. Installing VS 2022 Build Tools will cause unpinned pipelines to resolve to MSBuild 17 instead of the current version. To prevent unintended impact, all existing pipelines must be pinned to the current version BEFORE this installation.

**Change Conflict Justification:**
This installation is being performed outside the standard maintenance window due to the following factors:

1. The installation is additive only — no existing software is removed, upgraded, or reconfigured.
2. All existing pipelines will be pre-pinned to the current MSBuild version prior to installation, ensuring zero impact to running workloads.
3. The VS Build Tools installer supports silent installation with no reboot required (exit code 0) or deferred reboot (exit code 3010) that does not disrupt active runner jobs.
4. The runner can continue to accept and process jobs during and after installation with no service interruption.
5. No network, firewall, DNS, or infrastructure changes are involved.

**Does it impact the architecture of the app and/or app integration details?**
No. This change does not alter the application architecture or integration points. It adds a new build tool version to the runner's toolchain. No application code, deployment targets, network topology, or service integrations are modified.

