## 2. Planning Phase

### 2.1 Communication Plan

| Timing | Audience | Channel | Message |
|--------|----------|---------|---------|
| T-5 business days | All pipeline owners / dev teams | Email + Slack/Teams | Notification that MSBuild 17 will be installed. All teams must pin their workflows to vs-version `[16.0,17.0)` before the install date or their builds will auto-resolve to v17. |
| T-1 business day | All pipeline owners / dev teams | Email + Slack/Teams | Final reminder to pin workflows. Confirm pinning is complete before proceeding. |
| T+0 (post-install) | All pipeline owners / dev teams | Email + Slack/Teams | Confirmation that MSBuild 17 is available. Teams can opt in by setting vs-version `[17.0,)` or removing the pin. |
| T+0 (if backout) | All pipeline owners / dev teams | Email + Slack/Teams | Notification that the install was rolled back and the previous state has been restored. |

### 2.2 Justification

Development teams require MSBuild 17 (shipped with Visual Studio 2022) to build projects targeting newer .NET SDKs and to take advantage of performance improvements and 64-bit build support introduced in MSBuild 17.x. The current runner only has an older version of the Build Tools installed, which does not support these capabilities. Without this upgrade, teams are blocked from adopting modern .NET workloads on this runner.

- MSBuild 17 defaults to 64-bit builds, improving performance on large solutions.
- Required for projects targeting .NET 6+ and Visual Studio 2022 toolsets.
- Smaller binary log files and improved Terminal Logger output.
- Side-by-side installation — does not remove or alter the existing build tools.

### 2.3 Implementation Plan

1. **PRE-WORK (T-5 to T-1 days):** Communicate to all teams. Verify all existing pipelines have been updated to pin `vs-version: '[16.0,17.0)'` in their `microsoft/setup-msbuild@v2` step. Confirm no unpinned workflows remain.
2. RDP into the production Windows Server 2019 runner as a local administrator.
3. Open an elevated PowerShell session and run the `Install-MSBuild17.ps1` script. The script downloads the VS 2022 Build Tools bootstrapper, performs a silent install with MSBuild, .NET Desktop, and Web workloads, and validates the install via vswhere.
4. Verify MSBuild 17 is detected: run `vswhere -latest -requires Microsoft.Component.MSBuild -find "MSBuild\**\Bin\MSBuild.exe" -products *` and confirm the path points to the 2022 install.
5. Run a test pipeline (see Test Plan) to confirm MSBuild 17 resolves correctly.
6. Run an existing pinned pipeline to confirm it still resolves to the old MSBuild version.
7. Send post-install communication confirming MSBuild 17 is available.

### 2.4 Risk and Impact Analysis

| Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |
|------|-----------|--------|------------|
| Unpinned pipelines auto-resolve to MSBuild 17, causing build failures for teams not ready to upgrade. | Medium | High | All pipelines must be pinned to `vs-version: '[16.0,17.0)'` before installation. Pre-work verification step confirms compliance. |
| Installer requires a reboot (exit code 3010), temporarily taking the runner offline. | Low | Medium | Schedule install during low-activity period. If reboot needed, coordinate with teams and drain the runner first. |
| Disk space insufficient for the ~2–4 GB install. | Low | Low | Verify available disk space (minimum 10 GB free) before running installer. |
| vswhere does not detect the new install, causing setup-msbuild to fail. | Low | Low | Manually verify vswhere output post-install. If needed, specify vswhere-path in workflow YAML. |

**Overall Risk: Low.** This is an additive installation with no changes to existing software, configuration, or infrastructure. Downtime is not expected.

### 2.5 Backout Plan

If the installation causes issues, the backout is a clean uninstall of the VS 2022 Build Tools:

1. Open an elevated PowerShell session on the runner.
2. Run the VS installer in uninstall mode: `vs_buildtools.exe modify --installPath "C:\BuildTools\VS2022" --remove Microsoft.VisualStudio.Workload.MSBuildTools --remove Microsoft.VisualStudio.Workload.ManagedDesktopBuildTools --remove Microsoft.VisualStudio.Workload.WebBuildTools --quiet --wait`
3. Alternatively, for a full removal: navigate to Control Panel > Programs > Uninstall "Visual Studio Build Tools 2022", or run the bootstrapper with the `uninstall` flag.
4. Verify vswhere no longer returns a VS 2022 path: `vswhere -products * -format json`
5. Run a test pipeline to confirm setup-msbuild resolves to the original (old) version.
6. Communicate backout completion to all teams. Teams can remove their vs-version pins if desired.

*Estimated backout time: 10–15 minutes. No data loss or configuration drift is possible since this is a standalone tool installation.*

