|---|-----------|-----------------|-----------|
| 1 | Run `vswhere -latest -requires Microsoft.Component.MSBuild -find "MSBuild\**\Bin\MSBuild.exe" -products *` on the runner. | Returns path under `C:\BuildTools\VS2022\` pointing to MSBuild.exe. | |
| 2 | Run `MSBuild.exe -version` using the path from Test 1. | Reports version 17.x.x.x. | |
| 3 | Trigger a test GitHub Actions workflow using `setup-msbuild@v2` with `vs-version: '[17.0,)'` and run `msbuild -version`. | Workflow succeeds, msbuild -version outputs 17.x. | |
| 4 | Trigger an existing pipeline that is pinned to `vs-version: '[16.0,17.0)'`. | Workflow succeeds, msbuild -version outputs the original (older) version. | |
| 5 | Verify disk space post-install (`Get-PSDrive C`). | Adequate free space remaining (>10 GB). | |

### 2.7 Verification Plan

Post-implementation verification to confirm the change is stable and successful:

1. **Immediate (T+0):** All Test Plan cases pass. vswhere detects both the old and new Build Tools installations.
2. **T+1 day:** Monitor GitHub Actions workflow runs across all teams. Confirm no unexpected build failures related to MSBuild version resolution.
3. **T+3 days:** Follow up with early-adopter teams who have opted into MSBuild 17 to confirm builds are stable.
4. **T+5 days:** Review runner health — disk space, GitHub runner service status, no queued job backlog.
5. If any verification check fails, execute the Backout Plan and notify stakeholders.
